===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm}}, a {{bor|en|fro|abstinence|nocap=1}}, from {{der|en|la|abstinentia}}, from {{m|la|abstinēns}}, present participle of {{m|la|abstineō||I withhold}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈæb.stɪ.nəns/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|En-us-abstinence.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act or practice of [[abstaining]], [[refrain]]ing from [[indulge|indulging]] a desire or appetite. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=10}}</ref>
#: ''Penance, fasts, and '''abstinence''', / To punish bodies for the soul's offense.'' - [[w:John Dryden|John Dryden]]
#: ''The '''abstinence''' from a present pleasure that offers itself is a pain, nay, oftentimes, a very great one.'' — [[w:John Locke|John Locke]]
#: ''Complete '''abstinence''' is easier than perfect moderation.'' — [[w:Augustine of Hippo|St Augustine]]
## Specifically, the practice of abstaining from [[intoxicating]]/[[alcoholic]] [[beverage]]s; [[total abstinence]]; [[teetotalism]]). {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
## Specifically, the practice of abstaining from [[sexual intercourse]], either permanently or until [[marriage]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
## {{lb|en|ecclesiastical}} Abstention from certain foods on days of [[penitential]] [[observance]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# The practice of [[self-denial]]; self-restraint; forebearance from anything. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Self-denial; abstaining; or forebearance of anything. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|business}} Delay of spending to accrue capital.

